On 4/30/12 9:19 AM, jnoalexander wrote:
&gt; I&#39;m trying to crawl password protected pages. I&#39;m using the credential bean exactly as suggested. However, although the configuration compiles, it never seems to trigger submitting the form. Has anyone else got this to work?
&gt;
&gt;   I&#39;m using Heritrix 3.1.0. Any help appreciated!
&gt;
&gt; Bean details -
&gt; &lt;bean id=&quot;credential&quot;
&gt;     class=&quot;org.archive.modules.credential.HtmlFormCredential&quot;&gt;
&gt;      &lt;property name=&quot;domain&quot;&gt;
&gt;          &lt;value&gt;
&gt;              mydomain
&gt;          &lt;/value&gt;
&gt;      &lt;/property&gt;
&gt;
&gt;      &lt;property name=&quot;loginUri&quot;&gt;
&gt;          &lt;value&gt;
&gt;              my_place_to_submit
&gt;          &lt;/value&gt;
&gt;      &lt;/property&gt;
&gt;
&gt;      &lt;property name=&quot;formItems&quot;&gt;
&gt;          &lt;map&gt;
&gt;              &lt;entry key=&quot;username&quot; value=&quot;xxx&quot;/&gt;
&gt;              &lt;entry key=&quot;password&quot; value=&quot;xxx&quot;/&gt;
&gt;              &lt;entry key=&quot;Proceed1&quot; value=&quot;Sign in&quot;/&gt;
&gt;          &lt;/map&gt;
&gt;      &lt;/property&gt;
&gt; &lt;/bean&gt;

I believe the docs you consulted at...

&lt;https://webarchive.jira.com/wiki/display/Heritrix/Credentials&gt; and
&lt;https://webarchive.jira.com/wiki/display/Heritrix/HTML+Form+GET+or+POST&gt;

...were unclear and incomplete. It&#39;s not enough to just declare a 
top-level Credential bean: you need to make sure a CredentialStore is 
part of the crawl, *and* has any necessary Credentials inside its 
&#39;credentials&#39; map.

For this feature, a reasonable minimal example of its use is in the test 
class, HtmlAuthSelfTest.

I&#39;ve updated the docs to better reflect the necessary steps.

I&#39;ve also added a note that some login forms may exceed the ability of 
this HtmlFormCredential mechanism to submit a sufficient login. THe 
mechanism just submits a fixed set of form name/value pairs; while often 
that&#39;s enough to achieve a login, it&#39;s possible for forms to require 
extra less-predictable names/values.

For example, many forms nowadays include a hidden dynamic token as a 
guard against cross-site request-forgeries, aka &#39;XSRF&#39;. Heritrix&#39;s 
Form-authentication code hasn&#39;t been updated to perform the multiple 
steps of &lt;request, parse, merge with login/password, POST&gt; that would be 
required to login with such forms.

- Gordon
